What is AWS Global Infrastructure?

AWS operates data centers worldwide to provide highly available and fault-tolerant services.

Infrastructure consists of:

Regions
Availability Zones
Edge Locations
Region

A Region is a geographical location containing multiple data centers.

Examples:

ap-south-1
us-east-1
eu-west-1
Availability Zone

Each Region contains multiple Availability Zones.

Example:

Mumbai Region
│
├── AZ-A
├── AZ-B
└── AZ-C

Each AZ is physically separate.

If AZ-A fails:

Application
     ↓
AZ-B continues serving traffic
Edge Locations

Used by CloudFront CDN.

Purpose:

Faster content delivery
Reduced latency
Real-Time Scenario

Netflix stores content globally.

User from Chennai:

Request Movie
      ↓
Nearest Edge Location
      ↓
Movie Delivered

Fast performance worldwide.

Interview Questions:
Why Multiple AZs?

To achieve high availability and fault tolerance.

Difference Between Region and AZ?

Region = Geographical area

AZ = Data center inside Region
